(187, 'National park Lov&#263;en', 310, 0, NULL, 2, 'National park Lov&#263;en', 'National park Lov&#263;en', 'National park Lov&#263;en', 'National park Lov&#263;en', '<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="font-family: tahoma,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;"><img style="float: left; margin: 4px; border: 1px solid black;" title="Lov&#263;en" src="../upload-media/noncomm/lovcen.jpg" alt="Lov&#263;en" width="374" height="290" />It covers the central and highest part of Lovcen massif. It is located on the border of two regions, proudly raised above Bokoktorskog Bay, as the hinterland of Kotor. Its position has made it here, we find two types of air that create specific conditions for life, and here developed a special biosphere. In a small area one can find various types of terrain, which is particularly emphasized in the central part of the mountain.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="font-family: tahoma,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">Special value represent famous Lov&#269;enska serpentine, winding, old roads. One of them leads to the Lovcen Njegus, in which the hamlet, the house of the famous ruler and poet Petar II Petrovic Njegos, as well as the last ruler of Montenegro, King Nikola Petrovic</span></span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="font-family: tahoma,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">A friend and authentic architecture of this area, old houses and threshing, as I katunske huts. Bernard Dzordz Sho called the nahiye of Katuni, while he watched from a nearby lookout point, a sea of &#8203;&#8203;stone.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="font-family: tahoma,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">On top of Lovcen is the so-called " the highest grave in the world," a place of eternal rest Petar II Petrovic Njegos. This place he chose it for life and there he built a chapel which was later replaced by a magnificent mausoleum that made &#8203;&#8203;world famous sculptor Ivan Mestrovic.</span></span></p>', '42.399444', '18.818889', 'national-park-lov-263en'),
(188, 'Church of St. George', 322, 0, NULL, 2, 'Church of St. George', 'Church of St. George', 'Church of St. George', 'Church of St. George', '<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="font-family: tahoma,arial,helvetica,sans-serif;"><img style="float: left; margin: 4px; border: 1px solid black;" title="Crkva Svetog &#272;or&#273;a" src="../upload-media/noncomm/crkva_svetog_djordja.jpg" alt="Crkva Svetog &#272;or&#273;a" width="407" height="231" />At the foot of the hill Gorica is the church of St. George, the most important and oldest surviving Orthodox Church in Montenegro. It was built in the 11th Century, a style of building before Roman. Has undergone many alterations and the repairs, and elements of the style of today are not so visible. The church has one nave, with elongated nave characteristic of buildings between 10th and 12 Ages in Duklja. Once a very rich, the church was repeatedly destroyed and a large number of frescos and manuscripts destroyed. Part of the fresco from the 11th Century, however, survived, and most important are those that show the life of St. George. The bell tower is located on the west side. Legend has it that there was a tunnel which brought water from the Moraca monastery that stood here.</span></span></p>', '42.445490', '19.267111', 'church-of-st-george');
